(I) Find the interval(s) where the function $f(x)$ is monotonically decreasing on $[0,π]$;

(II) If ${x}_{0}∈(\frac{π}{2},π)$, $\sin {x}_{0}= \frac{3}{5}$, find the value of $f({x}_{0})$.

Given the function $f(x) = 2\sin\omega x\cos\omega x - 2\sqrt{3}\sin^2\omega x + \sqrt{3}(\_\omega (\_ > 0)), the lines $x = \_x\_{1}$ and $x = \_x\_{2}$ are any two symmetry axes of the graph of the function $y = f(x)$, and the minimum value of $|x\_1 - x\_2|$ is $\frac{\pi}{2}$.

1. Find the value of $\omega$;
2. Find the intervals where the function $f(x)$ is increasing;
3. If $f(\alpha) = \frac{2}{3}$, find the value of $\sin(\frac{5}{6}\pi - 4\alpha)$.

